commit.message:
linux/efa: Limit EQs to available MSI-X vectors

When creating EQs we take into consideration the max number of EQs the
device reported it can support and the number of available CPUs. There
are situations where the number of EQs the device reported it can
support and the PCI configuration of MSI-X is different, take it in
account as well when creating EQs.
Also request at least 1 MSI-X vector for the management queue and allow
the kernel to return a number of vectors in a range between 1 and the
max supported MSI-X vectors according to the PCI config.

Reviewed-by: Michael Margolin <mrgolin@amazon.com>
Reviewed-by: Yonatan Goldhirsh <ygold@amazon.com>
Signed-off-by: Yonatan Nachum <ynachum@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Update driver version to 2.12.0

Also updated release notes and RPM files.

Signed-off-by: Evgeny Ostrovsky <evostrov@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Print last interrupt time on tx timeout

Adding the timestamp of the last interrupt to the TX timeout routine.
This provides more information and may help identifying the reason of
the timeout.

Signed-off-by: Evgeny Ostrovsky <evostrov@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Remove redundant assert check and error prints

Remove WARN checks from ena_com_wait_and_process_admin_cq_polling
since once the execution flow reaches the check, it must be
ENA_CMD_COMPLETED because it can't be either of the other options:
1. ENA_CMD_ABORTED - in such case it will perform "goto err" in the "if"
   block above, thus skipping the WARN check.
2. ENA_CMD_SUBMITTED - in such case it will timeout inside the while(1)
   loop above and perform "goto err", thus skipping the WARN check.

Signed-off-by: Evgeny Ostrovsky <evostrov@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Add best practices info for rx_overruns

Since `rx_overruns` statistic has been introduced (See [1]),
customers have been facing occasional issues where the
statistic is increasing.
Adding an explanation about the statistic as well as
mitigation suggestions to the best practices page.

[1]: https://github.com/amzn/amzn-drivers/releases/tag/ena_linux_2.8.8

Signed-off-by: David Arinzon <darinzon@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Add support for XDP in RHEL 8.5 and above

Currently our driver supports XDP for kernels >= 5.0.
RHEL 8.5 (kernel 4.18.0-348) and above also support XDP.

This commit adds the necessary changes to kcompat.h
to enable support of XDP in the driver on RHEL 8.5
and above.

Signed-off-by: Arthur Kiyanovski <akiyano@amazon.com>
Signed-off-by: Evgeny Ostrovsky <evostrov@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Change error value in queue size calculation

Based on Linux documentation (See [1]), `EFAULT` indicates
a bad address, while `EINVAL` indicates an invalid argument.
As in this case, the value returned from the device is lower
than the expected minimum by the driver, it makes sense
to use `EINVAL`.

[1]: https://elixir.bootlin.com/linux/latest/source/include/uapi/asm-generic/errno-base.h

Signed-off-by: David Arinzon <darinzon@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Add support for reset request over AENQ

In order to support reset request message from the device to the driver,
over AENQ, which in turn should cause the driver to trigger reset, the
following was added:
1. New AENQ group - ENA_ADMIN_DEVICE_REQUEST_RESET, to support the
   new message from the device sent via the AENQ to the driver.
2. New reset reason - ENA_REGS_RESET_DEVICE_REQUEST, which is used in
   order to indicate that the reset was triggered by the driver
   following the device request.

Also added a new global statistic that stores the count of these
occurrences.

Signed-off-by: Evgeny Ostrovsky <evostrov@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Fix alignment of error prints

A fix for a checkpatch check named
`Alignment should match open parenthesis`, which requires
all parameters to be aligned to the parenthesis.

Signed-off-by: David Arinzon <darinzon@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Featurize AF_XDP support

There are functionalities in the code which are specific to AF_XDP.
This patch makes the necessary code modifications in order to surround
the entire code that's specific to AF_XDP with the proper macros.

Signed-off-by: David Arinzon <darinzon@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Backport API change in ethtool rxfh ops

This commit backports [1] which will be part of kernel 6.8.0.

Original commit message:
The get/set_rxfh ethtool ops currently takes the rxfh (RSS) parameters
as direct function arguments. This will force us to change the API (and
all drivers' functions) every time some new parameters are added.

This is part 1/2 of the fix, as suggested in [2]:

- First simplify the code by always providing a pointer to all params
   (indir, key and func); the fact that some of them may be NULL seems
   like a weird historic thing or a premature optimization.
   It will simplify the drivers if all pointers are always present.

- Then make the functions take a dev pointer, and a pointer to a
  single struct wrapping all arguments. The set_* should also take
  an extack.

This commit also declares the struct varaibles and allows us to remove
ifdefs from the ena_set_rxfh() and ena_get_rxfh() thus improving code
readability.

[1]: https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/netdev/net-next.git/commit/drivers/net/ethernet/amazon/ena?id=fb6e30a72539ce28c1323aef4190d35aac106f6f
[2]: https://lore.kernel.org/netdev/20231121152906.2dd5f487@kernel.org/

Signed-off-by: Ofir Tabachnik <ofirt@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Changes around strscpy usage in ena_config_host_info()

Few changes were introduced:
1. As noted in [1] strscpy is guaranteed to be NULL-terminated so we can
remove the -1 from the size.
2. Compilation fails on certain distributions when we ignore the return
value from strscpy therefore a check was added.
3. Added a newline after an strscpy if statement to adhere to Linux
style.

[1]: https://manpages.debian.org/testing/linux-manual-4.8/strscpy.9.en.html

Signed-off-by: Ofir Tabachnik <ofirt@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Backport strncpy to strscpy change

This commit backports [1].

Since `strncpy` is deprecated for use on NULL-terminated destination
strings [2] and as such we should prefer more robust and less ambiguous
string interfaces, i.e. strscpy.

[1]: https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/netdev/net-next.git/commit/drivers/net/ethernet/amazon/ena/ena_netdev.c?id=378bc9a40ed8b6f1bac558a64b65d4754de89387
[2]: https://www.kernel.org/doc/html/latest/process/deprecated.html#strncpy-on-nul-terminated-strings

Signed-off-by: Ofir Tabachnik <ofirt@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Backport ethtool_puts() conversion

This commit backports [1] which will be part of kernel 6.8.0, a
conversion of few cases of ethtool_sprintf to ethtool_puts.

As explained in [2]:
The first case, with just two arguments:
ethtool_sprintf(&data, buffer[i].name), commonly triggers a
-Wformat-security warning with Clang due to potential problems with
format flags present in the strings [3].

The second, when it's used with format string: "%s"
ethtool_sprintf(&data, "%s", buffer[i].name) is just a bit weird with a
plain-ol' "%s".

This commit also converts the rest of the ethtool_sprintf() calls to
ethtool_puts() for cases when only two arguments are used or when the
call is of the type: ethtool_sprintf(&data, "%s", buffer[i].name);

[1]: https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/netdev/net-next.git/commit/drivers/net/ethernet/amazon/ena?id=e403cffff1a46ab1a95d3bc72e92634445d68328
[2]: https://lore.kernel.org/lkml/8f0e55ea-1c24-4d6b-9398-0cbc2bb58907@lunn.ch/T/
[3]: https://lore.kernel.org/all/202310101528.9496539BE@keescook/

Signed-off-by: Ofir Tabachnik <ofirt@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Modify Numa node update on io_poll

The device supports a PCIe optimization hint, which indicates on
which NUMA the queue is currently processed. This hint is utilized
by PCIe (as long as the cpu host supports this feature as well)
in order to reduce its access time by accessing the correct NUMA
resources and maintaining cache coherence, when copying rx buffers to
the host. This functionality is applicable for rx rings only, also this
is XDP indenepdent.

This commit updates the following:
1. Remove redundant tx_ring->numa_node update.
2. Update rx_ring for AF_XDP as well.

This commit also wraps the xsk ring check in #ifdef ENA_AF_XDP_SUPPORT,
since we don't want this code running if AF_XDP is not supported.

Signed-off-by: Evgeny Ostrovsky <evostrov@amazon.com>
Signed-off-by: Arthur Kiyanovski <akiyano@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Fix possible stuck tx packets when a tx drop occurs

This fix was suggested in [1].

In case there is a tx packet burst, where N packets are to be sent,
if the last packet in the burst is dropped in ena_start_xmit(),
the doorbell is not sent to the device for this burst.

In such a case, the first N-1 packets in the burst will not be sent
until the next time a doorbell is sent.

This commit fixes this issue by sending a doorbell after a dropped
packet if it is the last in a tx burst !netdev_xmit_more() and also
after checking that indeed there are descriptors sent to the device.

[1]: https://lore.kernel.org/netdev/CANn89iJRHuFgPrsezhm2DuAw7JmLL2ZkPhZaf2Ymuq+STUm-8w@mail.gmail.com/

Suggested-by: Eric Dumazet <edumazet@google.com>
Signed-off-by: Arthur Kiyanovski <akiyano@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Handle ENA_CMD_ABORTED case on admin queue interrupt mode

Currently admin_queue->stats.aborted_cmd counter is incremented if an
admin command status is ENA_CMD_ABORTED and only if the admin queue is
in polling mode.
This commit fixes handling the case of incrementing
admin_queue->stats.aborted_cmd if the admin queue is in interrupt
mode as well.

Signed-off-by: Ofir Tabachnik <ofirt@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Remove code duplication of XDP supported feature flags

XDP supported feature flags are duplicated twice in the code.
Create a single define for all flags and use it in all places.

Signed-off-by: Arthur Kiyanovski <akiyano@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Remove redundant ena_select_queue handler

The handler doesn't add any new logic in comparison to default kernel
handler since kernel v2.6.30 [1].
Also, there are few differences between the handler and the latest
kernel (v6.6) [2] implementation:
1. The kernel gives priority to XPS over rx recorded queue.
2. The kernel supports rx queue recorded based on subordinate traffic
classes.
Since there is no justification for such implementation of rx queue
recorded, we delete the handler and let the kernel use the default one.

[1]: https://github.com/torvalds/linux/blob/07a2039b8eb0af4ff464efd3dfd95de5c02648c6
[2]: https://github.com/torvalds/linux/blob/ffc253263a1375a65fa6c9f62a893e9767fbebfa

Signed-off-by: Evgeny Ostrovsky <evostrov@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Move ifdef related to netdev_xmit_more

This commit moves the ifdef related to netdev_xmit_more() to
kcompat.h, making the code cleaner.

Signed-off-by: Arthur Kiyanovski <akiyano@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Clarify units of total_tx_size

As size may vary based on the context, added a clarification
that the size in the `total_tx_size` variable is measured in
bytes.

Signed-off-by: David Arinzon <darinzon@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Remove xdp drops from total rx drops in ena_get_stats64()

Commit [1] added the xdp rx drops to the total rx drops reported
by ena_get_stats64().

There are 2 reasons for xdp drops in the ena driver:
1. A multibuffer packet has arrived, and is currently unsupported.
2. The ebpf program decided the packet should be dropped.

The first reason is expected, and will be removed once xdp multibuffer
support is added to the driver.
The second reason is also expected and intentional.

Other rx drops reported in ena_get_stats64() are reported
by the device and are not expected in normal circumstances.

Therefore this commit separates the 2 rx drop types.
Device drops will be reported via ena_get_stats64(),
reflecting cumulative dropped packets across all queues.
XDP-related drops will be reported via ethtool statistics,
reflecting per-queue XDP drops.

[1]: commit 42066c7add30 ("linux/ena: Take xdp packets stats into account in ena_get_stats64()")

Signed-off-by: Arthur Kiyanovski <akiyano@amazon.com>
Signed-off-by: David Arinzon <darinzon@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Fit print commands into a single line

Fitting the print string and the variables into the same line
as the print call.

Signed-off-by: David Arinzon <darinzon@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Move a debug print to show the correct value

In its previous location, the debug print showed the
previous value of `tx_pkts`, which is updated below it.
Moving the print to the end of the packet processing
iteration.

Signed-off-by: David Arinzon <darinzon@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Remove enum ena_admin_os_type

In order to send the os type to the device enum ena_admin_os_type
was used. Replace this enum with a single define for the Linux OS.

Signed-off-by: Ofir Tabachnik <ofirt@amazon.com>

linux/ena: RX ring submission queue optimization

RX ring submission queue descriptors are always located in host memory.
This optimization replaces the generic update tail method with a
tailored method for host memory type descriptors to avoid unnecessary if
statement.

Signed-off-by: Evgeny Ostrovsky <evostrov@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Fix memory barrier comment

The dma_rmb() memory barrier guarantees that the device set the
phase bit before continuing to read the rest of the descriptor.
Because the phase bit and the rest of the descriptor are in the same
cache line this ensures coherency of the data from the descriptor.

Signed-off-by: Ofir Tabachnik <ofirt@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Verify number of descriptors for copybreak

Copybreak logic assumes that a packet fits into one descriptor.
Copybreak size can be changed by the user, and if the length of the
first descriptor is less than or equal to copybreak value, the driver
will choose the copybreak path, even though the packets could be spread
across multiple descriptors. This results in dropped packets.
This commit adds a verification that the number of descriptors is one
as a condition to enter copybreak logic.

Signed-off-by: Ofir Tabachnik <ofirt@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Optimize ena_xdp_free_rx_bufs_zc() arguments

When calling to ena_xdp_free_rx_bufs_zc(), rx_ring pointer is already
calculated, so passing it instead of adapter and qid in order to avoid
recalculating it again inside the function, similar to tx function:
ena_xdp_free_tx_bufs_zc.

Signed-off-by: Evgeny Ostrovsky <evostrov@amazon.com>

linux/ena: Use local variables instead of direct access

The same fields from the `adapter` parameter are accessed
multiple times in the same function.
Assigning them to local variables for better code
readability.

Signed-off-by: David Arinzon <darinzon@amazon.com>
